Microsimulation R Package

Microsimulation is a form of individual-based simulation

  • Our package: https://github.com/mclements/microsimulation
    • Open source tool for planning cancer screening policies
    • Fast and flexible discrete-event simulation (DES)
    • Common random number support
    • In-simulation report reductions
    • Support for distributed/shared memory parallelism

Notable related work

  • Closed source MODGEN microsimulation language by Statistics Canada 1
  • … and recent open source re-implementation Openm++ 2
  • simmer DES library for specific process-oriented simulations, with model specification in R and a C++ core 3

Open source infrastructure

RngStreams
a random number streams library for C++4
SSIM
a C++ discrete event simulation library. The library defines the basic interface for a process and provides the main simulation scheduler 5
Boost libraries
for R library to be compliant with C++98 6
Rcpp
R/C++ interface library, extended to wrap vectors of tuples, and maps using tuples as keys 7

Pseudocode

for j in 1..J do                // iterate over people
  schedule events               // initialise events
  while queue is not empty do
    event = pop(queue)
    handle event: begin         // new state?
      schedule new events
      write to report
    end
  end
end

Parallelisation

  • computationally intensive to run the simulation with high precision
  • it is also computationally intensive to calibrate the model
  • Microsimulations are computationally intensive, particularly for model calibration.
  • Four different methods of parallelisation:
    1. Shared memory: R-parallel
    2. Shared memory: OpenMP
    3. Distributed memory: MPI
    4. Hybrid: OpenMP/MPI

1. Shared memory: R-parallel

2. Shared memory: OpenMP

3. Distributed memory: MPI

4. Hybrid: OpenMP/MPI

Benchmark

  • Eight core nodes on 16 node cluster
  • Software:
    • OpenMP with gcc version 4.8.1
    • R version 3.0.2
    • Open MPI version 1.4.1
  • Model further described in case study
  • Simulation size \(\text{10}^\text{7}\)

Case Study

  • Prostate cancer is the most common cancer diagnosis for men in both Sweden and the US
  • Opportunistic prostate-specific antigen (PSA) testing causes over diagnosis and under treatment
  • Cancer screening policies may be based on cost-effectiveness analysis (CEA)

Adapting the FHCRC model to Sweden

  • Based on a prostate cancer screening model from the Fred Hutchinson Cancer Research Center (FHCRC) 8 9
  • Incorporate Swedish input data
  • Calibrate (or fit) parameters using Swedish calibration targets
  • Validate the model predictions using Swedish data
  • Predict clinical outcomes and cost-effectiveness under a number of scenarios

Natural history modelling

  • A natural history (NH) model describes the course from being healthy, to disease onset, progression and death. The model is motivated by biological mechanisms.
  • Natural history modelling can be used to:
    • to generalise results from randomised controlled trials (RCTs)
    • predict effects for different screening protocols
    • calculate cost-effectiveness using predicted lifetime costs and quality of life.

Research question: How should we plan for better prostate cancer testing?

Parameters affecting screening include:

  • Test characteristics for different tests (e.g. PSA, S3M, 4K and PHI)
  • Screening ages
  • Re-screening intervals
  • Screening history
  • Screening test compliance (if invitations are organised)
  • Biopsy compliance
  • Treatment effectiveness
  • etc…

Prostate Cancer

  • PCa has the highest incidence and mort of all Ca in Swe males.
  • Incidence in Swe is comparable with contries using PSA testing for a long time, Swe still has a comparably high mortality.
  • Prostate cancer is the most common cancer diagnosis and the most common cause of cancer death in Swedish males.*
  • Prostate cancer incidence rates in Sweden are similar to other countries with frequent prostate-specific antigen (PSA) testing, while Swedish prostate cancer mortality rates are high.12

* http://www-dep.iarc.fr/NORDCAN/english/StatsFact.asp?cancer=261&country=752, accessed 2016-04-20

Todays unstructured screening with PSA is ineffective

  • Todays unstructured PSA testing is inefficient
    • There is to much testing of low risk men
    • …too many biopsies of benin and low grade cancers
    • and simultanously high risk men are not treated
Over testing
  • 38% of men with PSA < 1 have a new test within 2.5 years 13
Over diagnosis
  • 60% of all men biopsied are negative
  • 50% of all cancers diagnosed are Gleason 6 14
Under treatment
  • 30% of men aged 50–59 with PSA10 ng/ml do not have a biopsy within 2 years
  • 17% of men aged 50–69 diagnosed with advanced prostate cancer had PSA4 ng/ml six months or earlier with no action

Prostate cancer screening trials

  • Two large clinical trials
    • where the European -ERSPC- showed a decrease in 27% mortality reduction
    • in the American counterpart -PLCO- screening had no effect on mortality
    • It is believed that the lack of effect was due high PSA testing in the control arm
  • The European Randomised study of Screening for Prostate Cancer (ERSPC) found a prostate cancer mortality rate ratio of 0.73 (95% CI 0.610.88) after 13 years of follow-up.15
  • In contrast, the Prostate, Lung, Colorectal and Ovarian (PLCO) trial in the US indicated that organised PSA testing has little effect on prostate cancer mortality (due to control contamination).16

From randomised controlled trials (RCTs) to policy

  • RCTs are the gold standard for evidence on the effects of interventions
  • However they are expensive, slow to conduct, only address specific forms of intervention and may offer limited evidence on longer-term effects
  • How can we extrapolate from RCTs to other interventions and longer-term outcomes?
  • Either: Use the observed RCTs with expert judgement
  • Or: Simulate for interventions using a natural history model.

Cost-effectiveness intro

  • The cost-effectiveness from the microsimulation can be described using utilities and costs for screening intervention \(k\), such that:
\begin{align*} \mathrm{Effectiveness}_k =& \frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n \int_0^\infty \frac{dU_{ik}(t)}{(1+\delta)^t}\\ \mathrm{Costs}_k =& \frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^n \int_0^\infty \frac{dC_{ik}(t)}{(1+\delta)^t} \end{align*}

where we simulate for \(n\) individuals with index \(i\), with individual-based cumulative utilities \(U_{ik}(t)\) and costs \(C_{ik}(t)\) at time \(t\), with discounting \(\delta\) (e.g. \(\delta=0.03\)).

Cost-effectiveness

Conclusions

  • Microsimulation is increasingly being used to plan cancer screening (e.g. by CISNET, NICE, USPSTF).
  • Four-yearly testing would reduce costs and have similar effectiveness as current PSA testing
  • Coupling R and C++ eases software dissemination and allows for high-level R methods
  • The performance of the hybrid OpenMP/MPI came at the cost of significant re-factoring
